{"key":"processedPost-10083605","value":{"id":10083605,"first":10082661,"last":10210921,"when":1238555629,"utime":"04/01/09 06:13 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />What is the general range of time one can expect to wait before full colonization?</blockquote><br />That's like asking how fast can a blue car go.<br />Colonization time depends on spawn used, health and vigor of the culture, substrate and supplementation, CO2 levels, temperature, etc.<br />I've found that quart jars of rye berries take about a month to fully colonize from an agar wedge.&nbsp; If that jar is then used to inoculate a substrate bag with about 7 quarts of sterilized and <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Sawdust-Woodchips\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">supplemented sawdust/hardwood chips</a>, the bag takes about another month to colonize.&nbsp; If you then use a few of those substrate bags to inoculate an outdoor bed after danger of frost is past in the spring, it should be fully colonized and ready to fruit by fall.<br />It's important to plan P cyanescens beds and get the spawn started by around christmas time to make sure they're ready by the fall fruiting season.<br />RR","title":"Re: Psilocybe cyanescens mycelium"}}